('economics:3-4-price-stability:match:5e3370d2', 'economics', 'economics:3-4-price-stability', '3.4 Price Stability', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Real interest rate”?", "options": ["A sustained rise in the general level of prices over time", "The general price level growing at a low rate, e.g. the 2% target", "A negative inflation rate — the general price level actually falls", "The nominal interest rate minus the rate of inflation"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Real interest rate” means: The nominal interest rate minus the rate of inflation"}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:ea6ff4f7', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "A change in income tax is an example of", "options": ["fiscal policy", "international trade policy", "labour market policy", "monetary policy"], "hint": "Fiscal policy = the government''s taxation and spending. Monetary policy = interest rates and the money supply.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — fiscal policy</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Fiscal policy is the government''s use of taxation and spending. Monetary policy is the Bank of England''s use of interest rates and the money supply.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:b9263bfd', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q3", "question": "The table provides information about a country''s income tax system. Which tax system has the government decided to use?", "options": ["Lower tax when income increases", "The same tax for all incomes", "A progressive income tax", "A proportional income tax"], "caseStudy": "<table style=\"width:100%;max-width:420px;margin:12px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;font-size:14px;\">\n<tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);\"><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Income (£ per year)</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Total tax paid (£ per year)</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">10 000</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">1 000</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">20 000</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">3 000</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">30 000</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">10 000</td></tr>\n</table>", "hint": "Work out the tax as a PERCENTAGE of income at each level: 1,000/10,000, 3,000/20,000, 10,000/30,000. Is the percentage rising, falling or constant?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — A progressive income tax</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>As a percentage of income: £1,000/£10,000 = 10%; £3,000/£20,000 = 15%; £10,000/£30,000 = 33%. The PROPORTION taken rises as income rises — the definition of progressive. A proportional tax would take the same % at every level.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:9ca01f58', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q5", "question": "A more uneven distribution of wealth will be caused by a reduction in", "options": ["interest rates", "property prices", "taxes on inheritance", "wage increases"], "hint": "Which reduction lets wealth stay concentrated in the same families across generations?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — taxes on inheritance</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Inheritance tax breaks up large estates and redistributes wealth. Cutting it lets wealth pass down intact, so the distribution becomes MORE uneven.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:4d0d24e0', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q6", "question": "What is the most likely cost of this decision? An increase in:", "options": ["debt interest", "exports", "government spending", "unemployment"], "caseStudy": "<p>A government increases its budget deficit.</p>", "hint": "A bigger deficit means the government must borrow more. What must it then pay on that borrowing? (Careful — ''government spending'' is the decision itself, not a cost of it.)", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — debt interest</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A larger deficit must be financed by more borrowing, and that borrowing carries interest the government has to pay — a genuine cost. Higher government spending is the CAUSE of the bigger deficit, not a cost of it, and a deficit would tend to REDUCE unemployment.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:37c5d8a7', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q7", "question": "What might happen if inflation is above this target? Interest rates will:", "options": ["decrease to discourage saving", "decrease to encourage more investment", "increase to discourage consumer spending", "increase to encourage more borrowing"], "caseStudy": "<p>The UK government sets an inflation target.</p>", "hint": "Inflation is too HIGH, so the Bank wants LESS demand. Which direction does it move rates, and why?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — increase to discourage consumer spending</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Above-target inflation means demand is too strong, so the Bank raises rates to make borrowing dearer and saving more attractive — cutting consumer spending and easing the pressure on prices. Option D pairs the right direction with the wrong purpose.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:9645a946', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "What is NOT a purpose of government spending?", "options": ["To ensure everyone has access to health services", "To increase the welfare of the population", "To maintain a balanced current account", "To reduce inequality in the distribution of income"], "hint": "Read the NOT. Three are things spending directly does. The current account is about trade — spending isn''t the tool for that.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — To maintain a balanced current account</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Government spending funds health, raises welfare and redistributes income. The current account balance is about exports and imports and is not a purpose of government spending.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:6c6efbde', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "How can fiscal policy be used to achieve economic growth?", "options": ["A decrease in government spending to achieve a budget surplus", "An increase in interest rates will encourage households to save", "Improved education standards will increase the supply of labour", "Lower levels of taxation will encourage more household spending"], "hint": "The question says FISCAL policy — taxation and government spending. Interest rates are monetary policy; education is supply-side. And a surplus would SLOW growth.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — Lower levels of taxation will encourage more household spending</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cutting tax is fiscal policy and raises disposable income, spending and therefore demand and growth. B is MONETARY policy, C is SUPPLY-SIDE policy, and A would reduce demand and slow growth.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:878101fc', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q10", "question": "What is the total household spend once VAT is added?", "options": ["£84", "£484", "£534", "£576"], "caseStudy": "<p>VAT on most food products is 20%. VAT on fresh fruit is 8%. A household spends £400 on food products and £50 on fresh fruit.</p>", "hint": "Apply each VAT rate to its own item, then add BOTH totals together — the question asks for the total SPEND, not the tax.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — £534</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Food: £400 × 1.20 = £480. Fresh fruit: £50 × 1.08 = £54. Total spend = £480 + £54 = £534. Option A (£84) is the VAT alone; £484 applies 20% to only part of the bill.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:652011a3', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q14", "question": "What may lead to a balanced government budget?", "options": ["An increase in exports", "An increase in imports", "An increase in taxation", "An increase in the money supply"], "caseStudy": "<p>The government has a budget deficit.</p>", "hint": "A deficit means spending exceeds tax revenue. To close it you must raise revenue or cut spending. Which option does that?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — An increase in taxation</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A deficit is spending greater than tax revenue, so raising taxation increases revenue and moves the budget towards balance. Exports and imports affect the current account, not the government''s budget, and the money supply is monetary policy.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:8c928873', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q16", "question": "In how many years was the indirect tax revenue between £200bn and £250bn?", "options": ["7", "8", "9", "10"], "caseStudy": "<p>The chart shows the revenue for the UK government from indirect taxes from 2007 to 2017.</p>\n<img src=\"/images/economics/3-5-uk-indirect-tax-revenue-chart-extracted.png\" alt=\"Bar chart from the OCR exam paper showing UK government revenue from indirect taxes in £bn from 2007 to 2017: about 203 in 2007, 212 in 2008, 234 in 2009, 236 in 2010, 234 in 2011, 247 in 2012, 238 in 2013, 238 in 2014, then rising above 250 to about 276 in 2015, 274 in 2016 and 304 in 2017\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;max-width:460px;margin:14px auto;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;background:#fff;padding:6px;\" />", "hint": "Count the bars whose tops fall between the £200 and £250 gridlines. The last three years clearly exceed £250bn.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — 8</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>2007 (≈203), 2008 (≈212), 2009 (≈234), 2010 (≈236), 2011 (≈234), 2012 (≈247), 2013 (≈238) and 2014 (≈238) all fall between £200bn and £250bn — that is 8 years. 2015 (≈276), 2016 (≈274) and 2017 (≈304) are all above £250bn.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:897e343a', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q17", "question": "Which statement about a government''s balanced budget is correct?", "options": ["Expenditure on exports equals expenditure on imports", "Tax revenue comes equally from direct and indirect taxes", "Tax revenue is equal to government spending", "Total value added of all products produced equals total income"], "hint": "The government''s BUDGET is its spending versus its tax revenue. Exports and imports belong to the current account, not the budget.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Tax revenue is equal to government spending</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A balanced budget means what the government raises equals what it spends. Option A describes balanced trade (the current account), not the budget.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:acc8f5dd', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q19", "question": "A government increases income tax on higher income groups. Which of the following is a benefit of this policy?", "options": ["It affects incentives to work", "It encourages household savings", "It makes income distribution more even", "It reduces the reliance on benefits"], "hint": "The question wants a BENEFIT. Taxing the rich more and redistributing the revenue does what to the gap between rich and poor?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — It makes income distribution more even</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A progressive tax takes proportionally more from high earners, narrowing the income gap. Option A (\"affects incentives to work\") is usually a COST of the policy, not a benefit.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:a632b0ea', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q20", "question": "This is an example of a", "options": ["capital gains tax", "progressive tax", "tax on imports", "value added tax"], "caseStudy": "<p>The diagram shows the relationship between income and tax paid. It plots income on the horizontal axis against tax paid on the vertical axis, and the line rises more steeply as income increases — so the tax paid grows more than proportionally as income grows.</p>\n<p><em>⚠️ Note: the diagram itself is missing from this ExamBuilder-compiled paper; the description above reproduces what the original showed.</em></p>", "hint": "The line curves upward, so tax rises FASTER than income — meaning a bigger percentage is taken as income grows. Which tax type is that?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — progressive tax</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Tax paid rising more than proportionally with income means a higher PERCENTAGE is taken as income rises — the definition of a progressive tax. A proportional tax would be a straight line through the origin.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>⚠️ Note on this compiled paper</h5>\n<p>The diagram this question refers to is <strong>absent</strong> from the ExamBuilder-compiled PDF (the space where it should appear is blank). The case-study text above describes the standard diagram the question intends.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:b681e604', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q21", "question": "In which year did the UK''s total tax revenue increase the most?", "options": ["2014–2015", "2015–2016", "2016–2017", "2017–2018"], "caseStudy": "<p>The table shows the UK''s total tax revenue in £ billion GBP.</p>\n<table style=\"width:100%;max-width:420px;margin:12px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;font-size:14px;\">\n<tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);\"><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Year</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">UK Total Tax Revenue in £ billion GBP</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2012–13</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">473.8</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2013–14</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">493.6</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2014–15</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">515.3</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2015–16</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">533.7</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2016–17</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">569.3</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2017–18</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">594.3</td></tr>\n</table>", "hint": "Work out the INCREASE for each year — subtract the previous year''s figure. Don''t just look for the biggest number.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — 2016–2017</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The increases are: 2014–15 = +21.7; 2015–16 = +18.4; <strong>2016–17 = +35.6</strong>; 2017–18 = +25.0. The biggest rise is 2016–17. 2017–18 has the highest total revenue but not the biggest increase — the trap.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:8f27741a', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q22", "question": "The table provides information about the UK''s income tax system. Calculate the approximate percentage of taxable income paid in tax by someone earning £45 000.", "options": ["14%", "20%", "29%", "72%"], "caseStudy": "<table style=\"width:100%;max-width:400px;margin:12px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;font-size:14px;\">\n<tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);\"><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Taxable income</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Tax rate</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Up to £12 500</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">0%</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">£12 501 to £50 000</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">20%</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">£50 001 to £150 000</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">40%</td></tr>\n</table>", "hint": "The first £12,500 is taxed at 0%. Only the rest is taxed at 20%. Work out the tax, then express it as a percentage of the FULL £45,000 — not of the taxed portion.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — 14%</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Tax = 20% × (£45,000 − £12,500) = 20% × £32,500 = £6,500. As a share of total income: £6,500 ÷ £45,000 = 14.4% ≈ 14%. Option B (20%) is the marginal rate, not the average rate actually paid — the trap.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:7cd6612b', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q23", "question": "There is an increase in the rate of taxation on interest earned from savings. Which of the following is most likely to happen?", "options": ["Capital expenditure will increase", "Income distribution will improve", "Individuals will save more", "Workers will move abroad"], "hint": "Who earns most of the interest income in an economy — and so who pays most of this tax?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Income distribution will improve</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Interest income mostly accrues to the wealthy, who hold the most savings. Taxing it more heavily takes proportionally more from them, so the distribution becomes more even. Higher tax on savings would DISCOURAGE saving, so C is wrong.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:f5bda984', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q24", "question": "This is an example of which policy cost?", "options": ["Externalities", "Resistance to policies", "Time lags", "Unintended effects"], "caseStudy": "<p>The government recently reduced the level of state benefits to improve incentives for people to work. However, this policy has led to an increase in poverty among unemployed people.</p>", "hint": "The government aimed at one thing (work incentives) but caused something it did not intend (more poverty). What is that called?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — Unintended effects</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The policy''s aim was to improve work incentives; rising poverty among the unemployed is a side-effect the government did not intend. Time lags would be about the policy taking too long to work.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:fd209e9e', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q25", "question": "A budget deficit means that", "options": ["imports into a country exceed its exports", "tax revenue is less than government spending", "the current account will be in surplus", "the government has no money left to spend"], "hint": "The BUDGET is the government''s own finances. Option A describes a trade deficit — a different thing entirely.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — tax revenue is less than government spending</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A budget deficit is spending exceeding revenue, financed by borrowing. Imports exceeding exports is a TRADE deficit. A deficit does not mean the government has no money — it borrows.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:8a6c749e', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q26", "question": "A government has decided to increase economic growth by budgeting for an excess of expenditure over revenue. One problem that this might cause could be a", "options": ["balance of payments deficit", "fall in total demand in the economy", "lower indirect tax income", "rise in unemployment"], "hint": "An excess of spending over revenue is expansionary — it RAISES demand. So B, C and D all point the wrong way. Where does some of that extra spending leak to?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — balance of payments deficit</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Expansionary fiscal policy raises household incomes and spending, and some of that extra spending goes on IMPORTS — worsening the current account. The other three describe the opposite of what expansionary policy does.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:d0768319', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q28", "question": "An increase in the level of unemployment benefit is most likely to", "options": ["increase labour market flexibility", "increase the quantity of labour supplied", "reduce the quantity of labour supplied", "stabilise the level of demand for goods and services"], "hint": "If benefits rise, the gap between not working and working narrows. What does that do to the incentive to take a job?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — reduce the quantity of labour supplied</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher benefits reduce the financial incentive to take a job, so fewer people offer themselves for work — the supply of labour falls.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:5634aa82', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q29", "question": "Which of the following is the most likely cost to central government of a high level of unemployment?", "options": ["Encouraging the unemployed to move", "Higher taxes for those in work", "Increased spending on unemployment-related benefits", "Lower living standards for the workforce"], "hint": "The question asks for a cost to CENTRAL GOVERNMENT — money it must pay out. Higher taxes and lower living standards are costs to individuals.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Increased spending on unemployment-related benefits</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>More claimants means the government pays out more in benefits — a direct cost to its budget. Higher taxes and lower living standards fall on individuals, not the government.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:745c1eaa', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q30", "question": "Government spending and taxation policy is known as", "options": ["financial policy", "fiscal policy", "monetary policy", "supply-side policy"], "hint": "The definition of fiscal policy, word for word.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — fiscal policy</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Fiscal policy IS government spending and taxation. Monetary policy is interest rates and the money supply; supply-side policy aims to raise productive capacity.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:75b67e33', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q31", "question": "Which one of these events is most likely to increase investment spending by firms?", "options": ["A fall in the rate of corporation tax", "A fall in the level of sales revenue", "An increase in interest rates", "An increase in progressive taxes"], "hint": "Investment means firms spending on capital. Which option leaves firms with MORE profit to reinvest and a better return on doing so?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — A fall in the rate of corporation tax</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lower corporation tax leaves firms with more after-tax profit to reinvest and raises the return on investment. Falling sales, higher interest rates and higher progressive taxes all discourage investment.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:4de811bc', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q32", "question": "An increase in which of the following is an example of fiscal policy?", "options": ["Income tax", "Interest rates", "Minimum wage", "Money supply"], "hint": "Fiscal = taxation and government spending. Interest rates and the money supply are monetary policy; the minimum wage is a labour market policy.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — Income tax</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Income tax is a tax, so changing it is fiscal policy. Interest rates and the money supply are monetary policy tools; the minimum wage is a labour market intervention.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:63bf005b', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q33", "question": "At the end of a financial year, government expenditure has exceeded government revenue. This is an example of a:", "options": ["budget deficit", "budget surplus", "trade deficit", "trade surplus"], "hint": "Government spending vs government revenue = the BUDGET (not trade). Spending exceeds revenue = which way?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — budget deficit</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Expenditure exceeding revenue in the government''s own accounts is a budget deficit. Trade deficits concern imports and exports, not the government''s budget.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:exam:8f0b222d', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q34", "question": "A government decides to cut indirect taxes and increase the government benefits which households can claim. As a result, households are likely to have:", "options": ["a lower cost of living", "a lower level of demand", "a lower level of saving", "a lower standard of living"], "hint": "Cutting indirect taxes like VAT makes goods CHEAPER, and higher benefits give households MORE money. Both point the same way — so which option fits?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — a lower cost of living</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cutting indirect taxes reduces the prices households pay, so the cost of living falls — and higher benefits raise their incomes too. Both changes would RAISE demand and living standards, so the other options point the wrong way.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:c74bfa7e', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Fiscal policy is best defined as...", "options": ["Government spending and taxation policy", "Policies to raise the economy''s productive capacity", "Controlling the money supply", "The Bank of England setting interest rates"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Fiscal policy IS government spending and taxation. Interest rates and the money supply are monetary policy; raising productive capacity is supply-side policy."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:926e1c0a', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these is a DIRECT tax?", "options": ["Corporation tax", "VAT", "Excise duty on fuel", "Excise duty on alcohol"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Direct taxes are on income or wealth and paid by the person liable — corporation tax is on company profits. VAT and excise duties are indirect taxes on spending."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:c01b4ba8', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A budget deficit means that...", "options": ["Tax revenue is less than government spending", "Imports exceed exports", "The government has no money left", "The current account is in surplus"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A budget deficit is the government spending more than it raises, financed by borrowing. Imports exceeding exports is a TRADE deficit — a common distractor."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:87a15944', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Income £10,000 → tax £1,000; income £30,000 → tax £10,000. This tax system is...", "options": ["A flat tax", "Progressive", "Proportional", "Regressive"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "As a percentage: 10% then 33%. The PROPORTION taken rises with income — that is what progressive means. A proportional tax takes the same % at every level."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:43e5b6bf', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "With a £12,500 tax-free allowance and a 20% basic rate, someone earning £45,000 pays approximately what percentage of their income in tax?", "options": ["29%", "20%", "72%", "14%"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Tax = 20% × (£45,000 − £12,500) = £6,500. As a share of the FULL income: £6,500 ÷ £45,000 ≈ 14%. The 20% is the marginal rate, not the average actually paid."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:b2354736', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A government increases its budget deficit. The most likely cost is an increase in...", "options": ["Debt interest", "Government spending", "Unemployment", "Exports"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A bigger deficit must be borrowed, and borrowing carries interest. Higher government spending is the CAUSE of the deficit, not a cost of it, and a deficit tends to cut unemployment."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:e6525ebb', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these serves the objectives of economic growth and low unemployment?", "options": ["Raising interest rates", "A balanced budget", "A deficit budget", "A surplus budget"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "A deficit budget (spend more, tax less) raises demand, so firms produce more and hire more — targeting growth and jobs. A surplus targets low inflation and the balance of payments."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:6c6efbde', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "How can fiscal policy be used to achieve economic growth?", "options": ["An increase in interest rates will encourage households to save", "A decrease in government spending to achieve a budget surplus", "Improved education standards will increase the supply of labour", "Lower levels of taxation will encourage more household spending"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Only A is fiscal policy AND expansionary. B is monetary policy, C is supply-side policy, and D would reduce demand and slow growth."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:359f3046', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Government spending on HS2 becomes income for construction firms, who pay steel suppliers, who pay others. This is the...", "options": ["Reverse multiplier", "Crowding out effect", "Opportunity cost", "Multiplier effect"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Each round of spending becomes someone''s income, who spends again — multiplying the original injection through the economy. Cutting spending runs it in reverse."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:mcq:dadfb23f', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A government cuts benefits to improve work incentives, but poverty rises among the unemployed. This policy cost is called...", "options": ["Externalities", "Unintended effects", "Resistance to policies", "Time lags"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The government aimed at work incentives but caused something it did not intend. Time lags would mean the policy simply takes too long to work."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tf:4e0b392c', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A change in interest rates is an example of fiscal policy."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Interest rates are MONETARY policy, set by the Bank of England. Fiscal policy is the government''s taxation and spending."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tf:3d12abc3', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "VAT is a direct tax."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "VAT is an INDIRECT tax — it''s charged on spending and collected by the seller. Direct taxes (income tax, corporation tax) are on income or wealth and paid by the person liable."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tf:107de3c7', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A budget deficit is the same as a trade deficit."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "A BUDGET deficit is government spending exceeding tax revenue. A TRADE deficit is imports exceeding exports. Both appear as MCQ distractors."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tf:53cf439b', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A deficit budget targets economic growth and low unemployment."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Spending more and taxing less raises demand, so firms produce more and hire more. A SURPLUS budget targets low inflation and a better balance of payments."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tf:45dc6547', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "An indirect tax on petrol shifts the supply curve to the left."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "The tax raises firms'' costs of production, so supply falls — label the new curve ''S + tax''. Price rises, quantity falls, and CO2 emissions fall with it."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tf:ab79208b', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Cutting income tax always increases consumer spending."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "An unintended effect: households may SAVE the extra money if they''re worried about the economy, or spend it on IMPORTS — so demand for domestic output may not rise at all."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tf:1b5e5c3c', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Increasing government spending always raises output."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Only if supply can respond. If the economy is near full employment and firms can''t produce more, the extra demand causes demand-pull INFLATION instead."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tf:e79b6b9a', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Fiscal policy involves an unavoidable opportunity cost."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "To spend more the government must cut spending elsewhere, raise taxes, or borrow more. There is always a trade-off — which is why the spec names opportunity cost explicitly."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:learn:08044fe7', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Fiscal policy — taxation and government spending", "reading": "<p><strong>Fiscal policy is all the choices the government makes about how it raises money (taxation) and how it spends it.</strong> It is the government''s own budget — NOT interest rates, which are monetary policy.</p>\n<h4>Direct vs indirect taxes — the difference the exam wants</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Direct taxes</strong> are taxes on <strong>income or wealth</strong>, where the person liable pays it themselves. Income tax, corporation tax (on business profits), inheritance tax, capital gains tax, National Insurance, council tax.</li>\n<li><strong>Indirect taxes</strong> are taxes on <strong>spending</strong>, collected by someone else and passed on. VAT; excise duty on cigarettes, alcohol and fuel.</li>\n<li>The precise mark-scheme wording: with a <strong>direct</strong> tax the person/organisation liable must pay it; with an <strong>indirect</strong> tax it is paid by another person/organisation to the one liable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Where the money comes from</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The biggest sources are <strong>income tax, VAT and National Insurance</strong> — together just over half of all government income. Then corporation tax, excise duties, business rates and council tax.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Where the money goes — the purposes of spending</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Social protection</strong> (pensions, unemployment benefits, sickness support) is by far the biggest area, then <strong>health</strong> and <strong>education</strong>, then defence, transport and public order.</li>\n<li>Purposes: ensuring everyone can access health services, raising welfare, and reducing income inequality. (Maintaining a balanced current account is NOT a purpose of spending — a real MCQ.)</li>\n<li><strong>Debt interest</strong> — about £56 billion. The longer a deficit runs, the higher the debt and the more interest must be paid in future.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What is the difference between a direct and an indirect tax?", "options": ["A direct tax is set by the Bank of England", "A direct tax is bigger than an indirect tax", "Direct taxes fund health; indirect taxes fund defence", "A direct tax is paid by the person liable for it; an indirect tax is collected and passed on by someone else"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Direct = the liable person pays it (income tax). Indirect = a tax on spending that the seller hands over (VAT). That is the mark scheme''s exact distinction."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:learn:dec49702', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "The budget — deficit, surplus and balance", "reading": "<p>The government''s plans for spending and taxation are set out in its <strong>budget</strong>. Fiscal policy has four objectives: <strong>economic growth, low unemployment, price stability and a better balance of payments</strong>.</p>\n<h4>The three budget positions</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Balanced budget:</strong> planned spending = expected income. (i.e. <strong>tax revenue equals government spending</strong> — that exact wording is a real MCQ answer.)</li>\n<li><strong>Surplus budget:</strong> spending &lt; income — achieved by spending less or raising taxes.</li>\n<li><strong>Deficit budget:</strong> spending &gt; income — achieved by spending more or cutting taxes. The gap must be <strong>borrowed</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What each budget does — and which objectives it serves</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Surplus:</strong> less government demand and higher taxes → demand falls → less pressure on prices and lower wage costs → UK firms more competitive → more exports. So a surplus targets <strong>low inflation + a better balance of payments</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Deficit:</strong> more spending and lower taxes → demand rises → firms produce more and hire more. So a deficit targets <strong>economic growth + low unemployment</strong>.</li>\n<li>The UK has generally run a deficit — the last surplus year was <strong>2000</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The vocabulary that earns marks</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A budget is in <strong>DEFICIT</strong> or <strong>SURPLUS</strong> — never \"bigger\" or \"smaller\". The examiners penalise the loose version explicitly.</li>\n<li>Don''t confuse a <strong>budget</strong> deficit (government spending vs tax revenue) with a <strong>trade</strong> deficit (imports vs exports). Both appear as MCQ distractors.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A government''s budget is balanced when...", "options": ["Direct and indirect taxes raise equal amounts", "Exports equal imports", "Tax revenue is equal to government spending", "The government has no debt"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The budget is the government''s own spending versus its revenue. Exports equalling imports is balanced TRADE — a different thing, and a deliberate MCQ distractor."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:learn:546c4a37', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How taxes and spending affect the economy", "reading": "<p>Every 6-marker here wants a CHAIN. Learn these four.</p>\n<h4>Direct taxes</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Income tax DOWN</strong> → workers keep more of their wages → labour supply rises AND disposable income rises → consumption rises → total demand rises → firms produce more → growth and jobs.</li>\n<li><strong>Corporation tax DOWN</strong> → firms keep more profit and the return on investment rises → more investment → more jobs. (Corporation tax UP discourages investment.)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Indirect taxes</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>VAT UP</strong> → goods cost more → demand falls. <strong>VAT DOWN</strong> → goods cheaper → the cost of living falls and demand rises.</li>\n<li><strong>Excise duty UP</strong> is aimed at goods with <strong>negative externalities</strong> (tobacco, alcohol, fuel) — raising the price to cut consumption. On a diagram: the tax raises production costs → <strong>supply shifts LEFT</strong> (\"S + tax\") → price rises → quantity falls. How far quantity falls depends on <strong>PED</strong> — and demand for tobacco and petrol is inelastic, so it falls only a little.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Government spending and the multiplier</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Government spending is INCOME to the firms it buys from. HS2 money becomes income for construction firms → they pay steel suppliers → those firms pay others → workers spend in local shops. Each round creates jobs and income: the <strong>multiplier effect</strong>.</li>\n<li>Cutting spending runs it in <strong>reverse</strong> — a vicious circle of falling income, fewer jobs and falling demand.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Subsidies</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Money given to producers or consumers to <strong>encourage</strong> goods with <strong>positive externalities</strong> — e.g. renewable energy, or the UK''s vaccine subsidy that lifted measles coverage from 81% to over 91%.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "An indirect tax is placed on petrol. On a supply and demand diagram this...", "options": ["Shifts supply right, cutting price", "Shifts supply LEFT, raising price and cutting quantity", "Has no effect on the diagram", "Shifts demand left, cutting price"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The tax raises firms'' costs of production, so supply shifts left (label it ''S + tax''). Equilibrium price rises and quantity falls — and less petrol burned means lower CO2 emissions."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:learn:72b763c1', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Evaluating fiscal policy — costs and unintended effects", "reading": "<p>The spec asks you to evaluate the <strong>costs, including opportunity cost, and the benefits</strong>. The examiners want you to see past the textbook effect.</p>\n<h4>The benefits</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Tax cuts raise disposable income; spending on merit goods (education, health, transport) brings positive externalities; higher demand raises output, living standards and employment; confidence rises; the multiplier magnifies it all.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The costs</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A wider deficit</strong> → more government debt → more <strong>debt interest</strong> to pay, and possibly higher interest rates.</li>\n<li><strong>Inflation</strong> — likely unless productive capacity also improves, and most likely near full employment.</li>\n<li><strong>Crowding out</strong> of the private sector; spending may go to inefficient projects; political motives may drive it.</li>\n<li><strong>Opportunity cost is unavoidable.</strong> To spend more the government must cut elsewhere, raise taxes, or borrow. There is always a trade-off.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Unintended effects — the highest-value evaluation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Cut income tax expecting more work → people may work <strong>less</strong> and earn the same.</li>\n<li>Cut income tax expecting more spending → people may <strong>save</strong> it (if worried about the economy) or spend it on <strong>imports</strong>, worsening the balance of payments.</li>\n<li>Raise spending expecting more output → if supply <strong>can''t</strong> respond, you get <strong>demand-pull inflation</strong> instead.</li>\n<li>Cut benefits to improve work incentives → <strong>more poverty</strong> among the unemployed. This is literally a real MCQ, answer: \"unintended effects\".</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>The judgement lever:</strong> nearly every fiscal evaluation turns on whether there is <strong>spare capacity</strong>, and on whether households actually <strong>spend</strong> the tax cut rather than save it.</p>", "question": "The government cuts benefits to improve work incentives, but poverty rises among the unemployed. This is an example of...", "options": ["Unintended effects", "Externalities", "Time lags", "Resistance to policies"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The aim was better work incentives; rising poverty is a side-effect the government did not intend — the definition of an unintended effect."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:misc:dd554982', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Unemployment fell, so the government''s budget got smaller.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The Assessment for Learning note on this paper singles this out: a significant number of candidates wrote about the budget becoming ''bigger or smaller'' rather than using the correct terms. The budget is the DIFFERENCE between spending and tax revenue, so it isn''t ''big'' or ''small'' — it is in DEFICIT or SURPLUS. When unemployment falls, revenue rises AND benefit spending falls, so the right phrasing is: a SMALLER DEFICIT, a move NEARER TO BALANCE, or a LARGER SURPLUS. The related trap is confusing a BUDGET deficit (government spending vs tax revenue) with a TRADE deficit (imports vs exports) — both are offered as MCQ distractors on this very paper.</p>", "question": "Unemployment falls, so tax revenue rises and benefit spending falls. The correct description of the budget effect is...", "options": ["The budget gets smaller", "A smaller deficit / a move towards surplus", "The budget gets bigger", "A trade surplus"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The budget moves between deficit and surplus. ''Bigger/smaller budget'' was explicitly flagged as the wrong terminology, and ''trade'' concerns imports/exports, not the budget."}'::jsonb)
